<article>
    <h1>Is It Pos&#xAD;si&#xAD;ble To Nip Di&#xAD;a&#xAD;betes In The Bud?</h1>
    <h2>Man&#xAD;age pre&#xAD;di&#xAD;a&#xAD;betes well to re&#xAD;duce your risk of de&#xAD;vel&#xAD;op&#xAD;ing Type 2 di&#xAD;a&#xAD;betes</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201113/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-13"><time>2020-11-13</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Sin­ga­pore­ans eat well — so well that di­a­betes has be­come a ris­ing prob­lem. About one in nine peo­ple in Sin­ga­pore have Type 2 di­a­betes — that puts us at the num­ber two spot, just be­hind the United States for di­a­betes rates.</p>
    <p>But be­fore this chronic ill­ness strikes, pa­tients ac­tu­ally first go through a stage called “pre­di­a­betes” — when blood sugar levels are higher than nor­mal, but not high enough for a di­a­betes di­ag­no­sis. This can be a make-or-break pe­riod; con­tinue to overeat and stay seden­tary and you are on the fast track to full-blown di­a­betes, but pull the brakes and start liv­ing healthy, and your con­di­tion can be re­versed.</p>
    <p>The Di­a­betes Pre­ven­tion Pro­gramme, a three­year study done in the United States found that by mak­ing changes to diet, ex­er­cise and life­style habits alone, par­tic­i­pants re­duced their risk of Type 2 di­a­betes by 58 per cent.</p>
    <p>“I re­mem­ber a pa­tient who, through proper diet and reg­u­lar ex­er­cises, lost 20kg from his orig­i­nal 90kg weight and had his pre­di­a­betes re­versed,” adds Dr Philip Koh, se­nior fam­ily physi­cian from Health­way Med­i­cal Group.</p>
    <p>Here are some life­style changes you can make now to man­age pre­di­a­betes.</p>
    <p>1. Choose low-fat, high-fi­bre foods such as fruits, veg­gies and whole grains, along with low gly­caemic in­dex (GI) items like whole­meal bread and brown rice over re­fined carbs. Fi­bre slows down the rate of digestion, which leads to a   slower, more grad­ual re­lease   of the car­bo­hyrates from whole grains into the blood­stream, which pre­vents spikes in   blood sugar levels.</p>
    <p>2. Aim for 30 to 60 min­utes of ex­er­cise five times a week. If you are over­weight, los­ing just five to 10 per cent of your body weight can help re­duce your risk of de­vel­op­ing Type 2 di­a­betes, says Dr Koh.</p>
    <p>Ex­er­cis­ing may also im­prove blood flow to the legs and feet. Poor blood cir­cu­la­tion is caused by high glu­cose levels in your blood, which may dam­age the lin­ing of small blood ves­sels. Ac­cord­ing to the United King­dom’s Na­tional Health Ser­vice, ex­er­cis­ing reg­u­larly for six months can lead to a 20 per cent im­prove­ment in an­kle blood pres­sure.</p>
    <p>3. On top of ex­er­cis­ing, reg­u­larly mas­sage your lower limbs to im­prove blood cir­cu­la­tion and oxy­gen flow. Re­duced blood flow to the lower parts of the body may lead to com­pli­ca­tions in the feet of di­a­betic pa­tients, which in­clude nerve dam­age and in­fec­tions. Con­sider us­ing MedicFlow Plus from Owell that use se­quen­tial air com­pres­sion to pro­mote blood cir­cu­la­tion and re­lieve swelling, stiff and sore mus­cles. Visit www.ow­ell­body­care.com to find out more.</p>
    <p>4. Quit smok­ing. Ac­cord­ing to a study pub­lished in the Jour­nal of In­ter­nal Medicine, smok­ing leads to in­sulin re­sis­tance, and as a re­sult may cause a rise in blood glu­cose levels.</p>
    <p>This ar­ti­cle was first pub­lished in Shape Sin­ga­pore, with ad­di­tional re­port­ing by Jo­lene Limuco.</p>

